        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>end-blown trumpets [300042354], trumpets (aerophones) [300042339], lip-vibrated aerophones with cylindrical bore [300209194], lip-vibrated aerophones [300041639], aerophones [300041622], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hooked bronze trumpets of the Etruscans and Romans, consisting of a slender tube with a cylindrical bore, terminating in an upturned bell. The term continued in use in postclassical times, meaning crumhorns or cornetts, though in the 18th century it denoted brass instruments.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000026541/Marcuse, Musical Instruments Dictionary (1975)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Trompetas etruscas y romanas de bronce en forma de gancho consistentes en un tubo delgado con diámetro interior cilíndrico, terminando en una campana doblada hacia arriba. Este término continuó en uso en los tiempos post clásicos para referirse a los cromornos o cornetas, aunque en el siglo XVIII se usó para designar a los instrumentos de bronce.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Haakvormige, bronzen trompetten, bestaande uit een slanke buis met cilindrische boring en een naar boven gebogen klankbeker; oorspronkelijk ontwikkeld en bespeeld door de Etrusken en de Romeinen.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052453/Algemene muziekencyclopedie (1961)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>伊特魯里亞人和羅馬人的鉤形青銅製小號，由纖細的筒管所製成，有著圓柱形內管，末端為向上翹起的號口。此詞彙一直沿用到後古典時期(postclassical times)，意指克蘭管和木管號，但在十八世紀時，泛指各種銅管樂器。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Hakenförmige Bronzetrompete der Etrusker und Römer, bestehend aus einer engen Röhre mit zylindrischer Bohrung, die in einem nach oben gekrümmten Schalltrichter endet. Die Bezeichnung wurde in der nachklassischen Zeit weiterverwendet in der Bedeutung von Krummhorn oder Zink; im 18. Jahrhundert bezeichnete sie dagegen Blechblasinstrumente.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
